ophets as the epitome of religious enthusiasm in early Enlightenment England. Based on new archival research, it retraces the formation, development and evolution of their movement and sheds new light on key contemporary issues such as millenarianism, censorship and the press, blasphemy, dissent and toleration, and madness.  aMode of access: Internet via World Wide Web.  aIn English.0 aDescription based on online resource; title from PDF title page (publisher's Web site, viewed 06. Mrz 2024) 0aCamisardszEngland. 0aEnthusiasmxReligious aspectsxChristianity. 0aProphecyxChristianityxHistoryy18th century. 7aHISTORY / Europe / Great Britain / General.2bisacsh  aCamisards.  aDissent.  aEnlightenment.  aEnthusiasm.  aHuguenots.  aMadness.  aMillenarianism.  aProphecy.  aToleration.1 aLaborie, Lionel, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb08iTitle is part of eBook package:dDe GruytertManchester University Press 2015 eBook-Packagez978311128311140uhttps://doi.org/10.7765/978178499725040uhttps://www.degruyter.com/isbn/9781784997250423Coveruhttps://www.degruyter.com/document/cover/isbn/9781784997250/original  a978-3-11-128311-1  Manchester University Press 2015 eBook-Packageb2015  aGBV-deGruyter-alles